Task 7: Identify and Remove Suspicious Browser Extensions

 Objective

The objective of this task is to identify installed browser extensions, analyze their permissions, and remove any suspicious or unnecessary extensions to improve browser security awareness.

---

Tools Used

Google Chrome 

Chrome Extensions Manager (chrome://extensions)

---

 Extensions Identified

During the inspection, the following extensions were found installed in the browser:

1)Google Docs Offline

Purpose: Allows viewing and editing Google Docs, Sheets, and Slides without internet access

Version: 1.99.1

Permissions:

Read and change data on Google Docs and Google Drive sites


Assessment: Legitimate and safe (Official Google extension)


2) Adobe Acrobat: PDF edit, convert, sign tools

Purpose: View, edit, convert, and sign PDF files in the browser

Version: 25.12.1.2

Permissions:

Read browsing history

Manage downloads

Communicate with native applications


Assessment: Legitimate and trusted (Official Adobe extension)

---

Security Analysis

Both extensions are from trusted vendors (Google & Adobe)

Permissions requested are relevant to their functionality

No unknown, unused, or suspicious extensions were detected

---

Research: How Malicious Extensions Harm Users

Malicious browser extensions can:

Steal passwords and personal data

Track browsing activity

Inject unwanted advertisements

Redirect users to malicious websites

Slow down system performance

---

Final Summary

Total extensions reviewed: 2

Malicious extensions found: None

Suspicious extensions: None

Overall browser security status: Safe

---
